english:
  title: Preface to Poems on the Departure of Yi Chiping, Censor-at-Large of Gyeongsang Province
  author: Yi Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The boundary between the divine and the human is not easily spoken of. To serve the spirits and to govern the people—only an emperor views these as one undertaking. Yet their distinction is clearly demarcated and must not be confused. The Son of Heaven alone sacrifices to Heaven and Earth; the feudal lords sacrifice to mountains and rivers; the officials sacrifice to the five household deities. Those who recorded the rites have already made this clear.

    Since our state has taken exclusive dominion over the Eastern Han, for all the mountains and rivers within our borders that fall under the sacrificial canon, twice yearly we select court officials to perform these rites as substitutes. We call such envoys the "Messengers of Sacrifice and Report." Through them we observe whether the provincial governors are virtuous or base, we examine the customs of the people for good or ill, we investigate taxes and tribute, unify regulations, and conduct broad inquiries—all to administer rewards and punishments and to prepare for the throne's questions. We call such envoys the "Inspectors of Integrity." These two commissions combined, undertaking circuit inspections through districts and provinces, truly represent an ancient method of provincial inspection. Acting as the sovereign's proxy, such office carries both honor and prestige that no other mission can rival.

    Yet if we say the office is honored and prestigious, what then of the weight of its responsibilities? When ministers stand in court, their rank may be high or low—this we need not discuss. What matters is whether their authority suffices to execute their will. The Ministry of Personnel may elevate or demote officials; court scholars may counsel and remonstrate. These are positions of clarity, importance, and proximity to power—yet how do they compare to the Censorate, whose members grasp the tablet of office, maintain dignified bearing, stand within the palace halls, and speak with the assurance that their words will be heeded and their remonstrances heard? For one person to combine these two responsibilities is indeed rare.

    My fellow examination graduate from Wansan, Yi, has been selected from his post as Censor-at-Large and dispatched to inspect Gyeongsang Province. He is precisely one who unites these two roles. Thus the officials and scholars of court have composed poems in celebration of his departure. The Gentleman Gwak, serving as Remonstrator, came to request my preface, saying it was Yi's own wish. I replied: "Yi is a man of solid character and practical integrity, employing keen and nimble abilities. In his service both within and outside the capital, his reputation and achievements have been illustrious. It is fitting that he should take his place at the Censorate and again grasp the authority to act. In performing sacrifices and conducting provincial inspection, he will shine brilliantly upon all who see and hear. He shall surely convey to the spirits, and they shall surely respond and grant their favor. The winds and rains shall come in season, all blessings shall descend, the people shall dwell in peace, officials shall fulfill their duties, and a great harmony shall pervade the realm. When he returns, we may expect the songs of universal peace to rise from field and village, thereby glorifying the virtue of the throne. Thus I write this preface."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The title refers to Yi''s dual appointment: first as Inspector of Integrity (按廉), an office combining ceremonial and administrative functions; second, his concurrent position as Censor-at-Large (持平), the highest censorial rank responsible for remonstrance and impeachment.'
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase "grasp the tablet" (持斧) alludes to the inspector's symbolic authority, traditionally represented by the emblem of office.
  - key: ''
    value: Wansan (完山) was the ancient name for Jeonju, Yi's native place, commonly used as a place name for individuals of prominence from that region.
